<HEADLINE>
<P>
METRO DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: SUPERVISORS BALK AT BACKING HIGHER SALES 
TAX 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors balked Tuesday at endorsing 
legislation to increase the state sales tax, the key element of a proposal to 
raise money for new schools in the Santa Clarita Valley, unless the legislation 
is amended. 
</P>
<P>
The bill by Sen. Ed Davis (R-Santa Clarita) -- which would require approval by 
voters throughout the state -- would boost the sales tax by a quarter-cent per 
dollar and allow property taxes to be raised by a majority of voters instead of 
requiring approval by two-thirds. 
</P>
<P>
A report by the county chief administrative officer said the bill is unfair 
because income from the sales tax increase would go only to school districts 
with booming enrollments, and only to those that increase their property taxes, 
a difficult feat for large districts such as Los Angeles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
