<HEADLINE>
<P>
YOUTH GETS 22 YEARS IN HIGH DESERT GANG SLAYING 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
A 16-year-old gang member was sentenced Tuesday to the maximum term of 22 years 
and four months in juvenile custody for fatally shooting a popular Antelope 
Valley High School youth in what authorities described as that area's first 
gang-related killing. 
</P>
<P>
Under juvenile sentencing procedures, however, the youth will be released 
before his 25th birthday, prosecutors said. 
</P>
<P>
The youth pleaded guilty March 23 to second-degree murder in the Jan. 6 slaying 
of Christopher Sanford, 18, of Lancaster, who was leaving a party in Lancaster 
when he was shot, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
The youth also pleaded guilty to attempted murder in the wounding of Sheldon 
Culver, 20, of Lancaster, who was shot in the neck but later recovered. 
</P>
<P>
Authorities said the youth, a member of a Sylmar gang, shot at several youths 
who were chasing him from a party that he attempted to crash, but missed and 
struck Sanford, who died a short time later at a hospital. 
</P>
<P>
"He happened to be in the wrong place at the wrong time," said Los Angeles 
County Deputy Dist. Atty. Chesley McKay, who prosecuted the case. 
</P>
<P>
Investigators named the youth as a suspect after interviewing other party-goers 
who witnessed the shooting, a Los Angeles County Sheriff's Department spokesman 
said. The youth remained at large for several weeks but turned himself in to 
authorities Feb. 12. 
</P>
<P>
The shooting prompted an outpouring of grief by Sanford's schoolmates and 
teachers, who remembered him as a likable youth and a star goalie for the high 
school's soccer team. 
</P>
<P>
Although gang activity has been on the rise in the Antelope Valley in past 
years, sheriff's investigators said the shooting was the first gang-related 
fatality in the area. 
</P>
</TEXT>
