<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: FOUNTAIN VALLEY; 
</P>
<P>
FAMILY FILES CLAIM OVER CONCERT DEATH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The family of a Fountain Valley teen-ager who died in police custody outside a 
Grateful Dead concert at the Forum last December filed a wrongful death claim 
against the city of Inglewood on Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
The claim, potentially a precursor to a lawsuit, says Patrick Shanahan, 19, was 
the victim of "summary execution" by overly aggressive police officers who 
struck him with their batons, applied a chokehold and did not start emergency 
first aid when he stopped breathing, said Lawrence Trygstad, the family's 
attorney. 
</P>
<P>
Inglewood police have maintained that officers did not use excessive force. 
They said Shanahan was uncooperative and under the influence of drugs when 
police arrested him outside the Forum on Dec. 10. Officers took Shanahan to a 
nearby hospital after he stopped breathing. 
</P>
<P>
An internal police investigation of the incident is continuing. In addition, 
the Los Angeles County district attorney's office is investigating the police 
response, and the FBI is looking into whether Shanahan's civil rights were 
violated when police arrested him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
