<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY FOCUS: ORANGE; 
</P>
<P>
UCI MEDICAL CENTER PICKETED OVER TALKS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LANIE JONES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
About 30 medical technicians and supporters picketed UCI Medical Center for an 
hour Tuesday to demand a raise. 
</P>
<P>
At one point a security guard threatened to have demonstrators arrested for 
disturbing the peace, but the pickets dispersed peacefully, said psychiatric 
technician Les Lyon, president of the technicians' union. 
</P>
<P>
The technicians carried signs that said: "First Class Hospital -- Second Class 
Wages," and "Mary Piccione -- You Got A Good Raise. Now We'd Like One." 
</P>
<P>
Piccione, director of the medical center, earned $136,163 annually until 
December, when her pay was boosted to $143,600 a year, a medical center 
spokeswoman said. 
</P>
<P>
By contrast, Lyon said, the 714 members of his union -- a mix of licensed 
vocational nurses, ward clerks and medical technicians -- earn $1,400 to $3,000 
a month. 
</P>
<P>
Talks reached an impasse March 30, with union leaders seeking a 6% wage 
increase and administrators offering an average of 2.9%, Lyon said. Medical 
center officials could not be reached for comment. 
</P>
<P>
Lyon vowed to picket again soon if there is no movement in talks: "We've got to 
call some attention to this. This is my third year without a raise, and I'm 
looking at a 1% increase in salary. There's reason enough to be angry." LANIE 
JONES 
</P>
</TEXT>
