<HEADLINE>
<P>
CALIFORNIA IN BRIEF; 
</P>
<P>
SAN FRANCISCO; 
</P>
<P>
EPA ACCUSES BASE OF WASTE VIOLATIONS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times staff and wire reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency announced that notices of 
noncompliance have been served to the Marine Corps Logistics Base near Barstow 
for violations of federal hazardous-waste laws. 
</P>
<P>
EPA inspections showed that base annexes violated several provisions of the 
federal Resource Conservation and Recovery Act, which regulates the treatment, 
storage and disposal of hazardous wastes, officials said. Violations include 
operating unauthorized hazardous-waste management units; treating, storing or 
disposing of hazardous waste not authorized by an existing permit; failure to 
maintain proper records, and failure to comply with land disposal restriction 
requirements. The Marine Corps is required to respond to the notice within 30 
days, detailing efforts planned to bring the facilities into compliance with 
the law, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
