</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
P.M. BRIEFING; 
</P>
<P>
NTT PICKS CESAR PELLI-YAMASHITA FOR NEW HEAD OFFICE IN TOKYO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Wire Services 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
<P>
TOKYO 
</P>
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Bowing to growing U.S. pressures, Japan's domestic telecommunications company 
NTT announced today it has selected a U.S.-Japanese joint venture for 
construction of its new head office in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
Nippon Telegraph &amp; Telephone Corp. said Cesar Pelli &amp; Yamashita 
Associated Architects have been selected as contractors from among seven 
applicants. 
</P>
<P>
The contractors are a joint venture of Cesar Pelli &amp; Associates Inc. of New 
Haven, Conn., and the Japanese engineering company Yamashita Architects &amp; 
Engineering Inc. 
</P>
<P>
Cesar Pelli, professor of architecture at Yale University, has designed many 
buildings in the United States. 
</P>
<P>
The Cesar Pelli-Yamashita venture was selected after NTT's Evaluation and 
Screening Committee has carefully studied proposals submitted by applicants, 
the company said. 
</P>
<P>
NTT's project calls for a 30-story head office in Tokyo's expanding business 
center of Shinjuku. 
</P>
<P>
NTT said it had originally planned to select contractors from among Japanese 
companies but made the change in light of repeated U.S. calls on Japan to open 
up its construction market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
